                <div class="content-leftside">
                  <div class="breadcrumb"><a href="http://www1.uwindsor.ca">Home</a> / <a href="http://www1.uwindsor.ca/cs">School of Computer Science</a> / <a href="/cs/818/phd-program">Doctoral Program</a> / <a href="/cs/822/procedures-for-progress-tracking-of-doctoral-students" class="active">Tracking Procedures</a></div>                                      <h1 class="title">Procedures for Progress Tracking of Doctoral Students</h1>
                                                                                          <div id="node-822" class="node node-type-page"><div class="node-inner">
      <div class="content">
    <p class="rtecenter">
	Supplementary to the Regulations for the Doctoral Program<br />
	--Procedures for Progress Tracking of Doctoral Students<br />
	&nbsp;<br />
	Doctoral Admission and Progress Committee<br />
	November 28, 2005</p>
<p>
	This supplementary specifies details regarding the procedures to track the progress of doctoral students, based on the &ldquo;Regulations for the Doctoral Program in Computer Science, March 2003&rdquo;. The progress tracking consists of the following components:</p>
<ol>
<li>
		Qualifying examination;</li>
<li>
		Comprehensive examination;</li>
<li>
		Annual report;</li>
<li>
		Seminars;</li>
<li>
		Research proposal;</li>
<li>
		Dissertation defence. &nbsp;</li>
</ol>
<h3>
	1 Committees</h3>
<p>
	There are four committees that are relevant to the Doctoral Program:</p>
<ol>
<li>
		Graduate Committee:<br />
		It consists of the Director, the Doctoral Program Chair, the Master Program Chair and Associate Chair, and two elected faculty members.&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />
		&nbsp;</li>
<li>
		Admission and Progress Committee:<br />
		It consists of five elected faculty members. This committee
<ul>
<li>
				Hold regular meetings to discuss issues relevant to the Doctoral Program;</li>
<li>
				Review and recommend applications;</li>
<li>
				Administrate the Qualifying Examination;</li>
<li>
				Track progresses of Phd students by reviewing Forms 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5. &nbsp;<br />
				&nbsp;</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
		Doctoral Committee:<br />
		It consists of the supervisor of the student, two faculty members from School of Computer Science, one faculty member from other department. The tasks are:
<ul>
<li>
				Administrate and Evaluate Comprehensive Exam (Form 2)</li>
<li>
				Evaluate and file Annual Progress Report that is prepared by the student (Form 3)</li>
<li>
				Administrate and Evaluate Seminar (Form 4)</li>
<li>
				Evaluate the Research Proposal (Form 5)<br />
				&nbsp;</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
		Dissertation Defense Committee<br />
		This committee consists of members from Doctoral Committee plus one more external examiner who is an expert in the area of the dissertation work and is from outside of University of Windsor.</li>
</ol>
<h3>
	2 Progress Check List</h3>
<p>
	Progresses made by each student will be recorded in Form 1, which will be made available to the Admission and Progress Committee, Doctoral Committee and Graduate Committee.&nbsp; Form 1 will record all the milestones that the student has made, including the supporting documents such as presentation slides, research proposals, and links to published papers. &nbsp;<br />
	&nbsp;<br />
	It is mandatory that all the papers that are published by the students should be listed in Form 1. &nbsp;<br />
	&nbsp;<br />
	Admission and Progress Committee will review the progress made by each student every year. &nbsp;</p>
<h3>
	3 Qualifying Examination</h3>
<p>
	The procedure for qualifying examination is well developed. Refer to &ldquo;<a href="http://cs.uwindsor.ca/~jlu/phd/phdNotesOnQualifyingExam3.doc" target="_blank">Notes on qualifying exam, by Dr. Frost</a>. &ldquo; and &ldquo;phdReading list for exam winter 2005.doc, by Dr. Frost&rdquo; for the details.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	There are two changes in order to reduce the preparation time for the qualifying examination:</p>
<ul>
<li>
		Either &ldquo;Numerical analysis&rdquo; or &ldquo;Basic probability&rdquo; is optional in the examination;</li>
<li>
		Students who obtained A grades in related courses taken within past 5 years can waive the topic.&nbsp; For example, &ldquo;Programming&rdquo; topic will require 3 related courses.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</li>
</ul>
<p>
	Details of the required number of courses are listed below:</p>
<table border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2" style="width: 500px;">
<thead>
<tr>
<th scope="col">
				Topic</th>
<th scope="col">
				Number of relevant courses required</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<caption>
		Table 1</caption>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="white-space: nowrap;">
				Basic probability</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">
				1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="white-space: nowrap;">
				Discrete mathematics</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">
				2</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="white-space: nowrap;">
				Numerical analysis and computation</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">
				1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="white-space: nowrap;">
				Database systems</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">
				1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="white-space: nowrap;">
				Computer architecture</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">
				1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="white-space: nowrap;">
				Data structures</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">
				1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="white-space: nowrap;">
				Operating systems</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">
				1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="white-space: nowrap;">
				Software engineering</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">
				1</td>
</tr>
