<td style="white-space: nowrap;">
				Networking and Internet</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">
				1</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>
	<br />
	4 Comprehensive Examination</h3>
<p class="rteindent1">
	&ldquo;<em>The comprehensive examination is one in which the student is asked to demonstrate a reasonable mastery of the field of specialization; it is designed to test the student&#39;s command of knowledge and ability to integrate that knowledge, after completion of all or most of the graduate course work. Normally, this examination is completed during the second year of graduate study and is a prerequisite to admission to candidacy.</em>&rdquo;<br />
	&nbsp; &mdash;Regulations 2003</p>
<h4>
	4.1 Time of the comprehensive examination</h4>
<p>
	It is recommended for the students to finish the comprehensive examination by the end of the second year of his/her study. &nbsp;<br />
	&nbsp;<br />
	Under extreme cases, with the request of the supervisor and the student, the Doctoral Admission and Progress Committee can grant the deferral of the examination up to one year, i.e., a student must finish the examination by the end of the third year.</p>
<h4>
	4.2 Format of the examination</h4>
<p>
	The student is required to submit a short research survey no less than 3000 words to the Doctoral Committee at least one week before the examination. At the examination, the student makes a 30 minutes presentation to the Doctoral Committee. The presentation will be followed by an oral examination. The candidate will pass the candidacy only if the committee is satisfied that:</p>
<ul>
<li>
		The research survey indicates the student has identified a sufficiently narrow topic, which could form a viable basis for a Ph.D. dissertation, and</li>
<li>
		The candidate is sufficiently informed in the field of research that has been proposed.</li>
</ul>
<p>
	Upon successful completion of the Candidacy Examinations, the student is automatically classified as a candidate for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.<br />
	&nbsp;<br />
	The examination is open to public.</p>
<h4>
	4.3 Result of the examination</h4>
<p>
	Examination result is either satisfactory or unsatisfactory. The Doctoral Committee should file a report of the examination by filling the form (Form 2), and submit the related documents that include the presentation slides and research survey. &nbsp;<br />
	&nbsp;<br />
	If the committee is not satisfied with the examination result, they will request that the student re-take the examination, provided that the examination is held within the two years specified by the regulations. If the result is not satisfactory again, the student will be advised to withdrawn from the program. &nbsp;</p>
<h3>
	5 Annual Report</h3>
<h4>
	5.1 Excepts from the regulations</h4>
<p>
	&ldquo;Each student must complete an annual report that is to be evaluated by his/her Doctoral Committee. The purpose of the progress report is to assess the student&rsquo;s progress in his/her research and to ensure continual and constructive interaction with the Doctoral Committee. An assessment of the report is prepared by the student&rsquo;s Doctoral Committee after meeting with the student to assess his/her progress made up to that point in the program. The Doctoral Committee sends the report and assessment to the Graduate Committee which will review it. If the report demonstrates insufficient progress, the Graduate Committee may send formal warning to the student or make other decisions regarding the student&rsquo;s registration in the program.&nbsp; Progress reports are submitted each year by the 30th of April for students entering in September, and by the 30th of August for students entering in January.&rdquo;<br />
	&nbsp;<br />
	Students are required to submit the report to the Admission and Progress Committee by April 30.&nbsp; The Doctoral Committee will comment on the report. Admission and Progress Committee will submit the report to the Office of Graduate Studies by May 31.<br />
	&nbsp;<br />
	The student will report on the progress he/she has made in the past year, including papers, seminars, courses, or other relevant progress.&nbsp; Admission and Progress Committee will evaluate the report, and may send formal warning to the student or make other decisions regarding the student&rsquo;s registration in the program.</p>
<h3>
	6 Seminars</h3>
<p class="rteindent1">
	<em>&ldquo;Each Ph.D. student must present at least two publicly-announced seminars during the program, not including the proposal or dissertation defence. The purpose of the seminars is to ensure participation of each student in the academic life of the School of Computer Science. They also permit students to develop their oral presentation skills and to receive feedback on their research from the audience.&nbsp; </em></p>
<p class="rteindent1">
	<em>Each seminar will be attended by the student&rsquo;s supervisor and at least one other member of the Doctoral Committee. All members of the Doctoral Committee who are present will assess the quality of the presentation.</em></p>
<p class="rteindent1">
	<em>For each successfully presented seminar, the student will complete a &ldquo;Ph.D. Student Seminar Form&rdquo; to be signed by the Doctoral Committee members who were present at the seminar and send it to the Dean of the Faculty of Graduate Studies and Research.&rdquo;</em> &ndash;Regulations 2003</p>
<p>
	The Doctoral committee will submit the seminar report form and the lecture slides of the presentation to the Admission and Progress Committee.&nbsp; The slides will be made public within faculty members of the School of Computer Science. &nbsp;</p>
<h3>
	7 Research Proposal</h3>
<p class="rteindent1">
	&ldquo;<em>After admission to candidacy, preparation for doctoral research involves assimilating the most important research papers on the topic; understanding how they relate to each other and identifying valid open research problems.&nbsp; The candidate must write a report, as part of the research proposal, containing a survey of work in the area, identification of the problem s/he has selected and a research plan with suggested approaches to solve the problem, and timelines and checkpoints. The report is then presented during an oral presentation to the Doctoral<br />
	Committee.&rdquo;</em>&mdash;Regulations 2003</p>
<h4>
	7.1 Time of the Proposal &nbsp;</h4>
<p>
	The candidate should present the proposal no later than the 3rd year, no later than I year before the thesis defence.&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>&lt;Note that this is changed from the calendar which says that proposal should be done within 2 years&gt;</strong></p>
<h4>
	7.2 Format of the proposal</h4>
<p>
	The student is required to submit a written research proposal no less than 4000 words, and to make a 40 minutes presentation to his/her Doctoral Committee. The presentation will be followed by an oral examination. The research proposal is open to public.</p>
<h4>
	7.3 Result of the proposal</h4>
<p>
	The result of the research proposal can be either Satisfactory or Unsatisfactory. The Doctoral Committee should submit the filled form, the research proposal, and the presentation slides.&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	If the Doctoral Committee deems the result is Unsatisfactory, the student has one chance to present a research proposal. If the student fails again, he/she will be required to withdraw from the program.</p>
<h3>
	8 Thesis Defence</h3>
<p class="rteindent1">
	<em>&ldquo;The candidate will present the dissertation to the Doctoral Committee and an External Examiner at a public defense. The Chair of a Ph.D. defense will be the Dean of Graduate Studies and Research or designate, such as the Dean of a Faculty or senior member of graduate faculty from outside the program, to be named by the Dean of<br />
	Graduate Studies and Research at the time the defense is publicly announced. The chair is non-voting. Questions will be permitted from the general audience at the discretion of the chair. The general audience may remain until the defense is completed and the committee begins its deliberations on the outcome. These deliberations are held in camera.&rdquo; </em>-&ndash; Regulations, 2003.&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	The external examiner should be an expert in the same area of the dissertation work, is from outside of the university, has not participated in the dissertation work, and has not co-authored papers with the student or the supervisor. Doctoral committee will suggest the external examiner to the Doctoral Admission and Progress Committee. The external examiner will be approved by Doctoral Program Coordinator and the dean of Graduate Studies and Research.&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />
	&nbsp;<br />
	&lt;Publication requirement to be developed&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>
<h3>
	9 Appendix: List of Forms</h3>
<ul>
<li>
		Form 1: Student progress check list, to be completed and tracked by graduate secretary;</li>
<li>
		Form 2: Comprehensive Exam Report (to be completed by the Doctoral Committee);</li>
<li>
		Form 3: Annual Progress Report (to be completed by the student and the Doctoral Committee);</li>
<li>
		Form 4: Seminar Report (to be completed by the Doctoral Committee).</li>
<li>
		Form 5: Research Proposal Report (to be completed by the Doctoral Committee).</li>
</ul>
<p>
	&nbsp;</p>
  </div>
